            <person xml:id="pers0199">
               <p>The eldest child of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0200.xml"
                     />Edward</persName> and <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0204.xml"/>Sarah
                     (Beecham) Bolton</persName>, from <placeName>Witney, Oxfordshire</placeName>,
                  Ann (&apos;Nancy&apos;) was exposed to Methodist preaching and joined the society
                  in <placeName>Witney</placeName> in <date when="1764-09">Sept. 1764</date>.
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> often stayed
                  with her and her brother <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0201.xml"/>Edward
                     Bolton</persName> (<date from="1747" to="1818">1747–1818</date>), a local
                  preacher, when he passed through <placeName>Witney</placeName> and
                     <placeName>Finstock</placeName>. Ann became one of <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s most frequent
                  correspondents through the last two decades of his life. After <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s death, Ann married
                     <persName>George Conibeere</persName> in <date when="1792">1792</date>. See
                  John Banks, &apos;<hi rend="italic">Nancy, Nancy</hi>&apos; (Wilmslow, Cheshire:
                  Penwork, <date when="1984">1984</date>); and Vickers, <hi rend="italic"
                     >Dictionary</hi>, 35–36.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
